{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17520465","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17520465"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:24:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:24:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13200"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13200","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13200"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.58,0.08,0.21,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5636"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105512"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5636","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5636"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13200"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87940"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"88"},{"type":"tags","id":"1659"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9613"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10557"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35593"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43387"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105512","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/105512"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 46-year-old man undergoes a kidney transplant. The procedure is uneventful and the patient is prescribed immunosuppressants to prevent rejection of the donor kidney. Prior to the procedure he was found to be PPD-negative and given the pneumococcal vaccine. He was also found to be HIV negative.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESix months later, the patient develops exertional dyspnoea and mild-moderate non-productive cough. On examination there are diffuse crackles bilaterally. On examination his blood pressure is 115/75 mmHg, pulse 79/min, temperature 37.2\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC, respiratory rate 14/min and SpO\u003Csub\u003E2\u003C/sub\u003E 94% on room air. A chest X-ray shows diffuse, bilateral symmetrical interstitial infiltrates extending from the perihilar region. An induced saline sputum sample shows clusters of cysts that stain with methenamine silver.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which is the following medications is most likely to have been prescribed in order to prevent this?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Valganciclovir","Trimethoprim/sulfamethoxazole","Dapsone","Fluconazole","Atovaquone"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe risk of infection is increased in solid organ transplant recipients and depends on a variety of factors. Antimicrobial prophylaxis following organ transplantation is highly specialised but this question tests knowledge of commonly occurring infections in the immunocompromised patients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has presented with features consistent with Pneumocystis jirovecii pneumonia (PCP) including gradual onset dyspnoea and non-productive cough. PCP typically has a more acute and severe clinical course in HIV-negative patients consistent with this case. The chest X-ray typically has fine reticular interstitial changes predominantly in a perihilar distribution. Diagnosis is confirmed with an induced sputum that stains positive for methenamine silver, cresyl violet and toluidine blue stain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERenal transplant patients usually require antimicrobial prophylaxis for:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPneumocystis jirovecii penumonia\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECytomegalovirus infection\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHerpes simplex virus infection\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPotentially other infections depending on past or present epidemiological risk (e.g. Strongyloids stercoralis and Burkholderia pseudomallei)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHepatitis B virus and tuberculosis reactivation\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EValganciclovir\u003C/strong\u003E is often used in the prevention of CMV infection and is usually started on day 10 after transplant. Alternatively ganciclovir is sometimes used depending on patient circumstances\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBactrim (trimethoprim+sulfamethoxazole)\u003C/strong\u003E is the most effective prophylaxis against pneumocystis jirovecii pneumonia. Prophylaxis is continued for at least 6-12 months after transplant or indefinitely if the patient has significant ongoing immunosuppression. Patients with sensitivity can undergo desensitisation provided do they not have severe hypersensitivity reactions (e.g DRESS, SJS/TEN).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDapsone\u003C/strong\u003E can be used for PCP prophylaxis but only in patients who are allergic to sulfa-containing medications and unable to undergo desensitisation. Other alternatives include pentamidine and atovaquone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFluconazole\u003C/strong\u003E is used for peri-transplantation prophylaxis of fungal infections such as candida. This is usually of concern in liver, lung or heart-lung transplantation patients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAtovaquone\u003C/strong\u003E can be used for PCP prophylaxis but is rarely used.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Trimethoprim+sulfamethoxazole is given after renal transplant to prevent pneumocystis jirovecii pneumonia and UTI","Valganciclovir and Ganciclovir is a common anti-viral used in prophylaxis of CMV infection in immunocompromised patients"],"references":["Weyant RB, Kabbani D, Doucette K, Lau C, Cervera C. Pneumocystis jirovecii: a review with a focus on prevention and treatment. Expert Opin Pharmacother. 2021 Aug;22(12):1579-1592. doi: 10.1080/14656566.2021.1915989. Epub 2021 Apr 19. PMID: 33870843. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33870843/","Pulmonary pneumocystis jirovecii infection: Radiopaedia Last revised by Yoshi Yu 25 August 2023. https://radiopaedia.org/articles/pulmonary-pneumocystis-jirovecii-infection-2?lang=gb#image_list_item_59581366 Accessed 10 December 2023."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87940"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13200"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87940","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/87940"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-09T16:41:31+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-09T16:41:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5636"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105512"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:52:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms